SIMPLE: orient
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Orient
<hw>O"ri*ent</hw> <pr>(⟦omac⟧"r⟦icr⟧*⟦eit⟧nt)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos>
<ety>[F., fr. L. <ets>oriens</ets>, <ets>-entis</ets>, p. pr. of
<ets>oriri</ets> to rise. See <er>Origin</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn>
<def>Rising, as the sun.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Moon, that now meet'st the <qex>orient</qex> sun.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Eastern; oriental.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧The
<xex>orient</xex> part.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Hakluyt.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Bright; lustrous; superior; pure; perfect; pellucid;
-- used of gems and also figuratively, because the most perfect jewels
are found in the East.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧Pearls round and
<xex>orient</xex>.⟦rdquo⟧ <au>Jer. Taylor.</au> ⟦ldquo⟧<xex>Orient</xex>
gems.⟦rdquo⟧ <au>Wordsworth.</au> ⟦ldquo⟧<xex>Orient</xex> liquor in a
crystal glass.⟦rdquo⟧ <au>Milton.</au>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Orient</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Orient
<hw>O"ri*ent</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The part of the
horizon where the sun first appears in the morning; the east.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>[Morn] came furrowing all the <qex>orient</qex> into gold.</q>
<rj><qau>Tennyson.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>The countries of Asia or the East.</def>
<rj><au>Chaucer.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Best built city throughout the <qex>Orient</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Sir
T. Herbert.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>A pearl of great luster.</def> <mark>[R.]</mark>
<rj><au>Carlyle.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Orient</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Orient
<hw>O"ri*ent</hw> <pr>(⟦omac⟧"r⟦icr⟧*⟦ecr⟧nt)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos>
<ety>[F. <ets>orienter</ets>. Cf. <er>Orientate</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn>
<def>To define the position of, in relation to the orient or east;
hence, to ascertain the bearings of.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <specif>Hence:</specif> <def>To acquaint with new
surroundings or a new situation.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Fig.: To correct or set right by recurring to first
principles; to arrange in order; to orientate.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>Same as <er>Orientate</er>, 2.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>To place (a map or chart) so that its east side,
north side, etc., lie toward the corresponding parts of the
horizon;</def> <specif>specif.</specif> <fld>(Surv.)</fld>, <def>to
rotate (a map attached to a plane table) until the line of direction
between any two of its points is parallel to the corresponding direction
in nature.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Oriental</ent>⟦br⟧
